      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "Since each term occurs twice in a syllogism, if any term is ambiguous it is possible that it occurs with two different meanings. In effect, such an argument has four terms, which violates the definition of \"categorical syllogism\", thus committing the fallacy of Four Terms. Moreover, if a word or phrase in such an argument ambiguously represents two terms, the argument commits the informal fallacy of Equivocation. Finally, if the argument equivocates on the middle term, it commits the fallacy of Ambiguous Middle.",
